I encountered the same problem. And, the reason is the onnx model with external data exceeds limitation 2GB, onnxruntime.InferenceSession() throw out this exception. Any onnxruntime release support  model larger than 2GB. i.e. LaBSE.onnx

issue.title: Runtime exception during initialization of SparkML model (One falsenode is pointing either to itself, either to another tree.)

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
Issue while loading a RandomForestClassifier model, exported as ONNX from PySpark using ONNX ml tools.

Exception trace seen:

> 2021-06-09 17:17:54.598724213 [E:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:1340 operator()] 
Exception during initialization: /onnxruntime_src/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/ml/tree_ensemble_common.h:167 onnxruntime::ml::detail::TreeEnsembleCommon<ITYPE, OTYPE>::TreeEnsembleCommon(int, int, const string&, const std::vector<IT>&, int64_t, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<IT>&, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<std::basic_string<char> >&, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<IT>&, const string&, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<long int>&, const std::vector<IT>&) [with ITYPE = float; OTYPE = float; std::string = std::basic_string<char>; int64_t = long int] **One falsenode is pointing either to itself, either to another tree**.


**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Linux 20.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): PyPI
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.0
- ONNX ML Tools version: 1.7.0
- Python version: 3.8
- PySpark version: 3.1.2
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): N/A
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): N/A
- CUDA/cuDNN version: N/A (using CPU inference)
- GPU model and memory: N/A

**To Reproduce**
- To reproduce the issue use the below python snippet to load the attached model  
   ```python
   def infer_from_onnx():
       input_list = [[randint(0, 20) for _ in range(32)]]
       sess = InferenceSession("<path to onnx model here>")
       print([x.name for x in sess.get_inputs()])
       input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
       output_name = sess.get_outputs()[0].name
       pred_onx = sess.run([output_name], {input_name: numpy.array(input_list, numpy.float32)})
       print(pred_onx)
   ```
- Summary of the attached model as reported from PySpark (5 trees, 32 features)
  ```
  RandomForestClassificationModel: uid=RandomForestClassifier_b21fc18d5170, numTrees=5, numClasses=2, numFeatures=32
    DecisionTreeClassificationModel: uid=dtc_d5dde2bcb50e, depth=2, numNodes=5, numClasses=2, numFeatures=32
    DecisionTreeClassificationModel: uid=dtc_6a76eaab2e06, depth=2, numNodes=5, numClasses=2,numFeatures=32
    DecisionTreeClassificationModel: uid=dtc_1b65c6c01b09, depth=2, numNodes=5, numClasses=2, numFeatures=32
    DecisionTreeClassificationModel: uid=dtc_a6a141e31c41, depth=1, numNodes=3, numClasses=2, numFeatures=32
    DecisionTreeClassificationModel: uid=dtc_6d6a063bbb17, depth=1, numNodes=3, numClasses=2, numFeatures=32
  ``` 
- Additional details:
  - The issue does not occur when we generate a model of (2 trees and 32 features)
  - Performing inference using a model with 2 trees and 32 features works fine.
  - Tried quite a few combinations of number of trees and features, there doesnt seem to be any specific pattern. It looks like some combination of tree count and feature count throws this issue.

**Expected behavior**
With the exported ONNX model, the inference should be possible.

**Additional context**
The issue seems to have been discussed in this [issue](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4486) with no conclusive solution due to lack of model files. I have attached the model files and the code for reproducing it. 

Code for creating a PySpark model:
```python
spark = SparkSession.builder.getOrCreate()
def create_model():
    df = spark.read.csv("<path to attached data csv here>", header=True, inferSchema=True)

    vec_assembler = VectorAssembler(
        inputCols=["c"+str(i) for i in range(FEATURE_LEN)], outputCol="features"
    )

    data = vec_assembler.transform(df)

    rf = RandomForestClassifier(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features", numTrees=5)

    model: RandomForestClassificationModel = rf.fit(dataset=data)
    model.save("./dummy_spark_model/model/")
```

Code for exporting the model to onnx:
```python
def export_as_onnx():
    model = load_model()
    model_onnx = convert_sparkml(
        model,
        "Phish Classifier",
        [("features", FloatTensorType([1, FEATURE_LEN]))],
        spark_session=spark,
    )
    with open("./dummy_spark_model/model/sp_model.onnx", "wb") as f:
        f.write(model_onnx.SerializeToString())
```

Code for performing inference is already listed in the section [**To Reproduce**]

[onnxmodel.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/6623577/onnxmodel.zip)
[features_32.csv](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/6628283/features_32.csv)
